'''''The Slip''''' is the seventh studio album by American [[industrial rock]] band [[Nine Inch Nails]], released on July 22, 2008. It was the fourth consecutive Nine Inch Nails release to be produced by frontman [[Trent Reznor]] with collaborators [[Atticus Ross]] and [[Alan Moulder]].  The album was released for free under a [[Creative Commons]] ([[BY-NC-SA]]) license, with the message from Reznor, "this one's on me."<ref name="LA Weekly">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.laweekly.com/music/music/nine-inch-nails-radiohead-free-music-and-creative-competition/18995/
  | title = Nine Inch Nails, Radiohead, Free Music and Creative Competition
  | date = 2008-05-28
  | first = Daphne
  | last = Carr
  | publisher = ''[[LA Weekly]]''.  [[New Times Media]]
  | accessdate = 2008-06-09}}</ref>  ''The Slip'' was initially released digitally via the Nine Inch Nails official website without any prior advertisement or promotion.  A limited-edition, physical version followed two months later, though this iteration of the album was not free.

''The Slip'' was originally intended to be an [[extended play|EP]], but eventually grew to be a full-length album.  It was recorded, performed, and released in three weeks; Reznor released the album's only single, "[[Discipline (Nine Inch Nails song)|Discipline]]", to radio stations himself, less than 24&nbsp;hours after it was mastered by Moulder. Critical reception of the album has been generally favorable, and its unorthodox method of release attracted significant media attention.  The album peaked at number&nbsp;13 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].

==Production==
===Background and recording===
Nine Inch Nails front man [[Trent Reznor]] announced in 2007 that the band had completed its contractual obligations to its record label, [[Interscope Records]], and would no longer be working with the company.  Reznor also revealed that Nine Inch Nails would likely distribute any future material independently.<ref name="Interscope split">{{cite web
  | last = Cohen
  | first = Jonathan
  | url = http://www.billboard.com/search/?keyword=nine+inch+nails&x=0&y=0#/news/nine-inch-nails-celebrates-free-agent-status-1003655498.story
  | title = Nine Inch Nails Celebrates Free Agent Status
  | accessdate = 2007-10-08
  | publisher = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.  [[Nielsen Company]]
  | date = 2007-10-08}}</ref>  Following the announcement, Nine Inch Nails released the 36-track instrumental album ''[[Ghosts I<U+2013>IV]]'' in March 2008 on Reznor's independent label [[The Null Corporation]].

Reznor returned to writing soon after the release of ''Ghosts'', and after a month of work ''The Slip'' was performed and recorded in three weeks of studio time at Trent Reznor's  in-home studio.<ref name="Frustration and Fury">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/08/arts/music/08pare.html
  | title = Frustration and Fury: Take It. It<U+2019>s Free.
  | publisher = ''[[The New York Times]]''.  [[The New York Times Company]]
  | last = Pareles
  | first = Jon
  | authorlink = Jon Pareles
  | date = 2008-06-08
  | accessdate = 2008-06-09}}</ref> The album was engineered by [[Atticus Ross]] and mixed by [[Alan Moulder]], both of whom co-produced it with Reznor. Originally intended as an [[Extended play|EP]], in Reznor's own words "it just kept growing legs until it [became] what it is".<ref name="It's Fun">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/sftw/article1497804.ece
  | title = I've always been afraid of not being good enough...for the first time, it's fun
  | first = Simon
  | last = Cosyns
  | work = [[The Sun (newspaper)|The Sun]]
  | publisher = [[News International]]
  | date = 2008-08-01
  | accessdate = 2009-05-24}}</ref> Some instrumental performances were contributed by [[Nine Inch Nails live performances|live-band]] members [[Josh Freese]], [[Robin Finck]], and [[Alessandro Cortini]], though they did not participate in the songwriting process; their contributions were limited to small parts rather than complete song recordings.<ref name="Vimeo interview">{{cite web
  | url = http://vimeo.com/4524660
  | title = Fans Q & A With Trent Reznor
  | publisher = [[Vimeo]].  [[IAC/InterActiveCorp]]
  | date = {{dts|2009|05|07}}
  | accessdate = 2009-08-19}}</ref>  During recording sessions, Reznor sent the album's first and only single, "[[Discipline (Nine Inch Nails song)|Discipline]]", to radio stations before the remainder of the album was completed, and less than 24&nbsp;hours after the track had been mastered.<ref name="Radio release">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.theninhotline.net/news/archives/backissue.php?y=08&m=4#1208889313
  | title = New song debuts on radio - Discipline
  | publisher = The NIN Hotline
  | accessdate = 2009-08-19}}</ref>  According to Reznor, the track listing and lyrics were finished on a Wednesday, the final [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]] and album sequencing on Thursday, the [[audio mastering|mastering]] on Friday, artwork on Saturday, and the album was released on Sunday, May 5.<ref name="Frustration and Fury" /> Reznor reflected on the quick turnaround by saying "that was fun [...] you never could have done that before", referring to the slow and bureaucratic pace of record production, promotion, and release he experienced with major record labels.<ref name="Frustration and Fury" />

===Music and lyrics===
[[File:Trent Reznor by Rob Sheridan.jpg|thumb|right|225px|alt=A man dressed in black walking through a desert at sunset.|Trent Reznor in a promotional Nine Inch Nails photo from 2008]]
Many critics noted how tracks on ''The Slip'' echoed musical stylings from the band's past, and that the record contained musical allusions to older Nine Inch Nails records.  Anastasia Pantsios of the ''[[Cleveland Free Times]]'' said that "''The Slip'' more or less sums up the terrain Reznor's covered in his nearly two-decade career", and went on to compare the album sound with the "edgy but irresistible beats" of ''[[Pretty Hate Machine]]'' and ''[[The Downward Spiral]]'', and "the elusive atmospherics" of ''[[The Fragile]]''.<ref name="Cleveland Free Times">{{cite journal
  | url = http://www.freetimes.com/stories/15/54/the-downloadable-spiral
  | title = The Downloadable Spiral
  | publisher = ''[[Cleveland Free Times]]''.  Kildysart LLC
  | issue = 54
  | volume = 15
  | date = 2008-05-14
  | first = Anastasia
  | last = Pantsios
  | accessdate = 2008-06-09}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  Jon Pareles of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that "the music revives Nine Inch Nails<U+2019> past, from stomping hard rock to dance-club beats to piano ballad to inexorably building instrumentals."<ref name="Frustration and Fury"/>  The album's final track, "Demon Seed", directly incorporates instrumental elements from the final track of the band's previous all-instrumental album ''Ghosts I<U+2013>IV''.<ref name="PM review">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/nine-inch-nails-the-slip/
  | title = Nine Inch Nails-The Slip
  | publisher = [[PopMatters]]
  | first = Mike
  | last = Schiller
  | accessdate = 2009-07-09}}</ref>

Ed Thompson of [[IGN]] commented that the tracks "Discipline" and "Echoplex" channeled "bits and pieces of [[Depeche Mode]], [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]], and even some [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]]".<ref name="IGN review">{{cite web
  | url = http://music.ign.com/articles/872/872307p1.html
  |title = Trent Reznor serves up some free goodies
  | last = Thompson
  | first = Ed
  |accessdate = 2008-05-09
  | date = 2008-05-07
  | publisher = [[IGN]].  [[News Corporation]]}}</ref> Richard Cromelin of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called ''The Slip'' "murkier and less catchy than the last couple of regular NIN albums", and added that "Reznor blends the jarring sounds of the industrial rock genre [...] with a terse, punk-like attack, bringing an insistent, sometimes claustrophobic feel to his scenarios of alienation".<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-et-nin7-2008may07,0,2146732.story
  | title = NIN<U+2019>s <U+2018>Slip<U+2019> a free dive in dark waters
  | accessdate = 2008-05-09
  | last = Richard
  | first = Cromelin
  |date = 2008-05-07
  | publisher = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.  [[Tribune Company]]}}</ref>  

Lyrically, Eric Harvey of [[Pitchfork Media]] compared "Discipline" to one of Nine Inch Nails's first singles, "[[Head Like a Hole]]", saying "['Discipline'] comes from a long-established and now label-free artist trying to reflexively reassert his position in the pop landscape, on his own terms. [...] 'Discipline' evinces Reznor's desire for some sort of framework [...] In relative terms, 'I need your discipline/ I need your help' is sure a long way from the nearly 20-year-old 'Head Like a Hole' refrain 'I'd rather die/ Than give you control'."<ref name="Pitchfork review">{{cite web
  | url = http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/11503-the-slip/
  | title = Nine Inch Nails: The Slip
  | publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]]
  | date = May 13, 2008
  | first = Eric
  | last = Harvey
  | accessdate = 2009-07-09}}</ref>  Tom Breihan of [[The Village Voice]] reached a similar interpretation of the album's lyrical content, writing "The Slip seems to deal with Reznor's break from the corporate machine, or at least from the numbing conformity-minded forces it represents."<ref name="VV review">{{cite web
  | url = http://blogs.villagevoice.com/statusainthood/archives/2008/05/maybe_its_insan.php
  | title = Nine Inch Nails' The Slip: A First Impression
  | publisher = [[The Village Voice]].  [[New Times Media]]
  | first = Tom
  | last = Breihan
  | accessdate = 2009-07-09}}</ref>

In commenting on the album, Reznor has said that it derived from "a weird sense of being outside [himself] in isolation and watching [himself] getting older."<ref name="It's Fun"/>  He also described it as "a quickly assembled album", and as "more of a sketch than a painting."<ref>{{cite journal
  | title = Screaming ahead
  | publisher = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.  [[Tribune Company]]
  | date = 2008-09-04
  | author = Geoff Boucher}}</ref>  Reznor compared the quick assembly of ''The Slip'' to the much longer process of creating his 1999 double album ''The Fragile'', saying that the creation of ''The Slip'' relied more on "reflexes" and that his next project would be given more "editorial time".<ref name="Frustration and Fury">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/08/arts/music/08pare.html?_r=3&ref=arts&oref=slogin&oref=slogin
  | title = Frustration and Fury: Take It. It<U+2019>s Free.
  | publisher = ''[[The New York Times]]''
  | last = Pareles
  | first = Jon
  | date = 2008-06-08
  | archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5YUa9v4NA
  | archivedate = 2008-06-11
  | accessdate = 2009-12-12}}</ref>

===Artwork===
[[File:Discipline.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A geometric pattern of five black squares in front of a gray background. A red line comes from the right and goes around one of the squares.|The artwork for "Discipline", an example of the geometric shapes of the album's visual design.]]
[[Rob Sheridan]], in collaboration with Reznor, was the album's art director, as he had been for the previous three Nine Inch Nails studio albums, ''Ghosts I<U+2013>IV'' (2008), ''[[Year Zero (album)|Year Zero]]'' (2007), and ''[[With Teeth]]'' (2005).  The downloadable version of ''The Slip'' comes with a [[Portable Document Format|PDF]] containing liner notes and album art.  Each track from the album is accompanied by its own graphic image, each of which consists chiefly of geometric patterns against a grey background.<ref name="PM review" />

==Release==
Trent Reznor posted on the official Nine Inch Nails website on April 21 a message saying "2 weeks!" Reznor employed a similar tactic to tease the release of the band's previous album (''Ghosts I<U+2013>IV'') earlier the same year.<ref name="RS 2 Weeks">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/04/22/nine-inch-nails-release-surprise-single-to-radio-announcement-in-2-weeks/
  | title = Nine Inch Nails Release Surprise Single to Radio, Announcement in <U+201C>2 Weeks!<U+201D>
  | publisher = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.  [[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]
  | last = Kreps
  | first = Daniel
  | date = 2008-04-22
  | accessdate = 2009-09-12}}</ref>  The following day, Reznor released the single by email "[[Discipline (Nine Inch Nails song)|Discipline]]" to radio stations and as a free download on the official Nine Inch Nails site.<ref name="RS 2 Weeks" />  Another song, "Echoplex", was released as a free download from [[iLike]] later.<ref name="NIN Hotline Echoplex">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.theninhotline.net/news/archives/backissue.php?y=08&m=5#1209776258
  | publisher = The NIN Hotline
  | title = New song: Echoplex
  | date = 2008-05-02
  | accessdate = 2009-08-19}}</ref> The [[ID3]] tags of these [[MP3]] files also pointed to the date May 5, just as Reznor's post had.<ref name="NIN Hotline Echoplex" /> On May 5, a free direct download link to the album in MP3 format was posted on the official Nine Inch Nails website, with a message from Reznor that said: "Thank you for your continued and loyal support over the years - this one's on me."<ref name="LA Weekly" />  The digital download is available in a variety of [[Digital rights management|DRM]]-free audio formats.  The lyrics for each track are embedded using ID3 tags, for viewing in supported media players.

Like the previous Nine Inch Nails studio album ''Ghosts I<U+2013>IV'', ''The Slip'' was released under a  [[Creative Commons]] [[Creative Commons licenses|attribution-noncommercial share-alike]] license, in effect allowing anyone to use or rework the material for any non-profit purpose, as long as credit is provided and the resulting work is released under a similar license.<ref name="Archive.org">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.archive.org/details/nine_inch_nails_the_slip
  | title = The Slip (May 5, 2008) <U+2013> Nine Inch Nails
  | publisher = [[Internet Archive]]
  | accessdate = 2008-06-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/us/
  | publisher = [[Creative Commons]]
  | title = Attribution-Noncommercial-Share Alike 3.0 United States
  | accessdate = 2009-09-02}}</ref> The website further expands this by saying "we encourage you to remix it, share it with your friends, post it on your blog, play it on your podcast, give it to strangers, etc."<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://blog.wired.com/music/2008/05/nine-inch-nails.html
  | title = Nine Inch Nails Gives Fans ''The Slip''
  | accessdate = 2008-05-05
  | last = Van Buskirk
  | first = Eliot
  | date = 2008-05-05
  | work = [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] 
  | publisher = Blog Network}}</ref>  As with ''Ghosts I<U+2013>IV'' and ''[[Year Zero (album)|Year Zero]]'', multi-track audio source files of the album were also made available at the official Nine Inch Nails remix site.  Reznor also plans on giving away the online software and digital infrastructure through which both ''The Slip'' and ''Ghosts'' were released.<ref name="Frustration and Fury" />

''The Slip'' was released on CD in the United States and Canada on July 22; unlike the digital release, however, the physical version of the album was not free. The physical package was released as a six-panel [[digipack]] which contained the album itself, a 24-page booklet, a sticker pack, and a DVD with live rehearsals of "1,000,000", "Letting You", "[[Discipline (Nine Inch Nails song)|Discipline]]", "Echoplex", and "Head Down".  Three of these videos were featured on Pitchfork Media prior to the CD/DVD release.<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://pitchfork.com/tv/#/episode/1969-nine-inch-nails-live-rehearsals/1
  | title = Nine Inch Nails - Live Rehearsals
  | publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]]
  | accessdate = 2009-08-25}}</ref> The physical release of the album was limited to 250,000 numbered units worldwide.  A 180-gram gatefold vinyl was released in the US and Canada on August 12, and in the United Kingdom August 18.<ref name="The Slip physical">{{cite web
  | url = http://theslip.nin.com/physical/
  | publisher = [[Nine Inch Nails]]
  | title = nine inch nails: the slip limited edition CD/DVD and deluxe vinyl
  | accessdate = 2009-08-19}}</ref>

==Reception==
===Sales and public reception===

A month and a half after its online release, ''The Slip'' had been downloaded 1.4&nbsp;million times from the official Nine Inch Nails website.<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://nin.com
  | archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5YvHvzNuD
  | archivedate = 2008-06-28
  | publisher = Nine Inch Nails
  | title = The Slip Download Map
  | accessdate = 2008-07-07}}</ref>  By the time the physical version was released two months later, that number had grown beyond 2&nbsp;million.<ref name="It's Fun" />  The physical release of the album has sold more than 98,000&nbsp;copies, and peaked at number&nbsp;13 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and the [[Billboard charts#Top Internet Albums|Top Internet Albums]] charts, based on weekly retail sales.<ref name="Allmusic albums">{{cite web
  | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p5033|pure_url=yes}}
  | publisher = [[Allmusic]].  [[Rovi Corporation]]
  | title = allmusic ((( Nine Inch Nails > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums )))
  | accessdate = 2009-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/musical/2009/09/14/090914crmu_music_frerejones
  | title = High Fidelity
  | last = Frere-Jones
  | first = Sasha
  | date = 2009-09-14
  | publisher = ''[[The New Yorker]]''.  [[Cond<U+00E9> Nast Publications]]
  | accessdate = 2009-09-14}}</ref>  The album also charted internationally, including number&nbsp;12 on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]], number&nbsp;22 on the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Albums Chart]], and number&nbsp;25 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].<ref name="Allmusic albums" /><ref name=AUSChart>{{Cite web
  | url = http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Nine+Inch+Nails&titel=The+Slip&cat=a
  | title = Nine Inch Nails Australian Charting
  | accessdate = 2009-08-17
  | publisher = Australian-charts.com Hung Medien}}</ref><ref name="UK Charts">{{cite journal
  |title = The Official UK Albums Chart for the week ending 9 August 2008
  |journal = [[ChartsPlus]]
  |issue = 363
  |pages= 5<U+2013>8
  |accessdate = 2008-08-10
  |publisher = IQ Ware Ltd
  |location = Milton Keynes}}</ref>  The album's only single, "[[Discipline (Nine Inch Nails song)|Discipline]]" reached number&nbsp;6 and number&nbsp;24 on ''Billboard''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Alternative Songs]] and [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]] charts, respectively, based on weekly radio airplay.<ref name="Allmusic singles">{{cite web
  | url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p5033|pure_url=yes}}
  | publisher = [[Allmusic]].  [[Rovi Corporation]]
  | title = allmusic ((( Nine Inch Nails > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles )))
  | accessdate = 2009-09-12}}</ref>

Following the release of ''The Slip'' and the similarly unorthodox release of ''[[Ghosts I<U+2013>IV]]'', Reznor confessed in retrospect that "It doesn't feel like an overwhelming success to me."<ref name="LV review">{{cite journal
  | publisher = ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]''.  [[Stephens Media (newspapers)|Stephens Media]]
  | title = Out of the Abyss
  | last = Bracelin
  | first = Jason
  | date = 2008-12-12}}</ref>

