Critical response to ''The Slip'' has been generally favorable, with an average rating of 78% based on eleven reviews on [[Metacritic]].<ref name="MetaCritic">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/nineinchnails/slip
  | title = Nine Inch Nails: The Slip (2008): Reviews
  | accessdate = 2008-05-17
  | publisher = [[Metacritic]].  [[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> [[IGN]] gave the album an 8.8 out of 10, stating "Simply put, ''The Slip'' is an amazing record."<ref name="IGN review" /> The ''[[Toronto Star]]'' said "[''The Slip''] is hardly a throwaway, this seems a sincere gift to fans."<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/Buzz/article/424164
  | publisher = ''[[Toronto Star]]''.  [[Torstar|Torstar Corporation]]
  | title = Ben Rayner's Reasons to Live . . .
  | accessdate = 2008-05-22
  | last = Rayner
  | first = Ben
  | date = 2008-05-11}}</ref> Eric Harvey of Pitchfork Media gave the album a 7.5 out of 10 and wrote "Reznor's unique capacity to commingle raging industrial bangers with ballads and ambient instrumental passages appears in its best form since ''The Downward Spiral'', and here gains much of the focus and restraint that many remember used to be his calling card."<ref name="Pitchfork review" />  Daphne Carr of ''[[LA Weekly]]'' said "Musically, it<U+2019>s his most adventurous work since The Fragile, and his business model is inspired <U+2014> if unsustainable."<ref name="LA Weekly" />  ''[[Slant Magazine]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s review was not as positive, however: Sal Cinquemani summarized in his review that "individual songs on The Slip aren't particularly dynamic", and described the track "Lights in the Sky" as "a tuneless, minimalist piano dirge".<ref name="Slant review">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=1379
  | publisher = [[Slant Magazine|Slant]]
  | title = Nine Inch Nails : The Slip <U+2013> Music Review <U+2013> Slant Magazine
  | first = Sal
  | last = Cinquemani
  | date = 2008-05-05
  | accessdate = 2009-09-19}}</ref>   Mikael Wood of [[Spin (magazine)|''Spin'']] complained that "a few tracks, such as 'The Four of Us Are Dying,' go on for far too long", but then said "Reznor recovers with a barn burner like 'Demon Seed'".<ref name="Spin review">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.spin.com/reviews/nine-inch-nails-slip-null-corporation
  | title = Nine Inch Nails, The Slip
  | publisher = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''.  Spin Media
  | first = Mikael
  | last = Wood
  | date = 2008-06-26
  | accessdate = 2009-07-09}}</ref>

As with ''Ghosts I<U+2013>IV'', ''The Slip'''s unorthodox distribution methods also garnered the attention of various news agencies. An [[ABC News]] [[op ed]] questioned if consumers would "ever pay for an album again" stating "with NIN now in the game, its [sic] hard to argue that this is anything but a harbinger of the future."<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://abcnews.go.com/Business/story?id=4813233&page=1
  | title = Will We Ever Pay for an Album Again?
  | accessdate = 2008-05-09
  | last = Malone
  | first = Michael
  | date = 2008-05-09
  | publisher = [[ABC News]]}}</ref> Commenting on the distribution of the album, Dave LaGesse of ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' said "The move seems an even purer play than what [[Radiohead]] did with its most recent album, ''[[In Rainbows]]''."<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://www.usnews.com/blogs/daves-download/2008/05/06/nine-inch-nails-100-percent-free-album.html 
  | publisher = ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''
  | title = Nine Inch Nails' '100 Percent Free' Album
  | last = LaGesse
  | first = David
  | date = 2008-05-06
  | accessdate = 2008-05-22}}</ref>  Jody Rosen of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine called giving away ''The Slip'' for free Reznor's "most radical stunt yet", and added that "[it's] an impressively democratic, fourth-wall-shattering gesture coming from one of music's biggest control-freak auteurs."<ref name="RS review">{{cite web
  | url = http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/20727302/review/20777267/the_slip
  | title = Nine Inch Nails
  | publisher = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.  [[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]
  | first = Jody
  | last = Rosen
  | accessdate = 2009-07-09}}</ref>  Eric Harvey of [[Pitchfork Media]] compared the release strategy of ''The Slip'' favorably to that of ''Ghosts I<U+2013>IV'' and ''[[Year Zero (album)|Year Zero]]'', writing that "[u]nlike its most immediate predecessors, The Slip comes packaged with a crucial difference: the music itself is more satisfying than the sui generis marketing scheme."<ref name="Pitchfork review" />

''Rolling Stone'' named ''The Slip'' in their "Best of 2008" list, ranking the album at number&nbsp;37, and named Reznor number&nbsp;46 in its "100 People Who Are Changing America" list, concluding that he has "been more creative than anyone in embracing the post-CD era".<ref>{{cite web 
  | url = http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/24958695/albums_of_the_year/24
  | publisher = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.  [[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]
  | title = The 50 Best Albums of 2008 
  | date = 2008-12-25
  | accessdate = 2008-12-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/26754176/the_rs_100_agents_of_change/7
  | title = The RS 100: Agents of Change <U+2013> The 100 People Who Are Changing America
  | publisher = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.  [[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]
  | date = 2009-03-18
  | accessdate = 2009-08-17}}</ref>  Following the release of the online-releases of ''The Slip'' and ''Ghosts I<U+2013>IV'', Reznor was awarded the "Webby Artist of the Year Award" at the annual [[Webby Awards]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/specialachievement13.php/
  | publisher = [[Webby Awards]], [[International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences]]
  | title = 13th Annual Webby Special Achievement Award Winners
  | accessdate = 2009-05-05}}</ref>

